.TH _PRINTF 3 "June 2025" "Holberton School" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
_printf \- formatted output conversion
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.sp
.BI "int _printf(const char *format, ...);"
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf()
function produces output according to a format string, similar to the standard
.B printf
function.

It writes output to the standard output stream (stdout) and returns the number of characters printed, excluding the null byte used to end output to strings.

The format string is composed of zero or more directives: ordinary characters (excluding '\0') and conversion specifications.

A conversion specification begins with a '%' character and ends with a conversion specifier.

.SH FORMAT SPECIFIERS
The supported conversion specifiers are:

.TP
.B %c
Prints a single character.

.TP
.B %s
Prints a null-terminated string.

.TP
.B %d, %i
Prints a signed decimal integer.

.TP
.B %%
Prints a literal percent sign.

.SH RETURN VALUE
On success, returns the total number of characters printed. On failure, returns -1.

.SH EXAMPLES
.EX
_printf("Hello %s!", "world");
Returns: 12
Outputs: Hello world!

_printf("Value: %d", 42);
Returns: 10
Outputs: Value: 42

_printf("Percent: %%");
Returns: 9
Outputs: Percent: %
.EE

.SH AUTHOR
Written by students at Holberton School.

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR printf(3)
